            "answer_text": "Yes. Today we tend to think of the ancient Greeks as corresponding to the modern nation state of Greece. This a massive mistake to make when discussing Classical and Medieval history. When studying history, we must be careful not to impose present circumstances onto our conception of the past. Historically until the age of the nation states, the Greeks lived all over the Mediterranean, and many of these regions were just as Greek as Athens. In 500 BC a person from a Halicarnassus in modern day Turkey would have considered himself as Greek as somebody from Athens, and the Athenian would likely have agreed with him. In the midst of the Greek golden age following the defeat of the Persian invasion, when Athens became famous for all of its philosophers, the biggest and most prosperous city-state of the Greek world was Syracuse, in Sicily. When Pyrrhus fought the Romans, he was not invading Italy, he was defending the Greeks of Magna Graecia (Great Greece) from a Roman invasion. The great father of history, Herodotus wrote his famous Histories living under the rule of the Persian Empire that he writes about so scathingly, in his native home of Halicarnassus in Asia minor. At the famous battle of Salamis, roughly half of the Persian navy came from its greek provinces in Asia minor, modern day Western Turkey. At the height of the Roman Empire the second greatest city of the Empire was the Greek city of Alexandria, in modern day Egypt. The Medieval Roman Empire which was pejoratively referred to by its Western peers as the \u201cGreek Empire\u201d had its capital at Constantinople, modern day Istanbul. Most modern day Turkish cities have their roots in Medieval Roman cities. (For those who don\u2019t know, when I say Medieval Roman, I\u2019m referring to the erroneously named Byzantine Empire). When the Turks showed up in Anatolia, it had been Greek speaking for almost 1000 years, with some regions having an even longer Greek history than that. In fact even under Turkish rule many regions remained primarily Greek. In fact Greek history in Anatolia really only ended in 1922, under the modern day Turkish Republic, when the Greek population was forced out at the conclusion of the Population exchange between Greece and Turkey (which was really more like two concurrent genocides than anything else) where the Historically Greek regions of Ionia (southwestern Anatolia), Pontus (Black Sea Coast), and Cappadocia (central Anatolia) were largely depopulated, with Istanbul also losing almost a third of its population. So it wouldn\u2019t be quite accurate to say that the Greeks lived in Turkey before the Turks arrived, but rather that before the Turks arrived Turkey was a part of Greece. ",
