            },
            "answer_text": "Describing Anatolia as a \u201chistorically gr\u2019eek land\u201d is against facts and realities, and in some cases, it is advocating the traditional \u201cMegali Idea\u201d propaganda of the modern gr\u2019eek state. The word \u201cYunan\u201d (gr\u2019eek in Turkish), was the name of the grand Persian satrapy in Western Anatolia under Darius, which was formed by Caria, Lycia and Pamphylia. These regions had never been \u201cgr\u2019eek\u201d in the classical meaning. Another point is that the word \u201cgr\u2019eek\u201d was not coined until the Roman conquest. That\u2019s why, the Hellenes who did not survive this conquest, not the so-called \u201cancient gr\u2019eeks\u201d, established colonies on the coastal parts of Morea and Aegean as three tribes : \u201cDorians, Ionians and Aeolians\u201d. The Thracians, who originated in Europe and inhabited Bithynia in the north and Nicaea (today\u2019s Iznik), resisted against the presence of these colonies. In the south, Caria was the continuation of Lydia. Carians and Lycians emerged as seperate ethnos following the dissolution of Lydia and these populations were certainly \u201canti-Gr\u2019eek\u201d. In the north, there was once again, the \u201canti-Gr\u2019eek\u201d Troy against Ionians and Aeolians. The other major ethnic groups were the Celtic-origined Galatians, and the Phrygians who migrated together with Thracians via Thrace region. Following the Macedonian conquest of Athens, the vast majority of Hellenes completely left the region. They were either sent into exile by Alexander, or began to serve as mercenaries under Persian rule. The fact is that the Persians did not launch a military campaign from Iran during their wars with Hellenes. Instead, the movement of Persian army started from the Aegean coast and resulted with the conquests of Peloponnese and Thessaly. Which confirms that regions such as Caria, Cilicia, Cappadocia and Bithynia, including the ancient kingdom of Pontus, were Persian satrapies as a whole. The usage of gr\u2019eek language in Anatolia was the result of the success of trade colonies. After the Roman conquest, Anatolia became a completely Latin-speaking region. Constantinople was established during this period as well. The Romans united the multi-ethnic structure and \u201canti-Gr\u2019eek\u201d folks of Anatolia under the roof of Christianity. Thus, a new \u201cRoman (Rum)\u201d ethnos emerged. The fact of Alexander speaking the language of ancient Hellenes does not \u201cHellenize\u201d these folks. In other words, the ethnic \u201cgr\u2019eek\u201d presence in the region came to an end during the era of Roman dominance. The \u201cAnatolian gr\u2019eek\u201d identity was based on religion. The Gr\u2019eek-speaking subjects of the Eastern Roman Empire managed to unite due to Orthodoxy. A historical \u201cgr\u2019eek\u201d identity in terms of a nation and demographic dominance never existed in Anatolia in any period of history. ",
